ading fails the CLI exits with an actionable error message,\" which suggests error handling matters. If directory creation fails due to permissions, should the CLI provide a meaningful error? The behavior statement itself doesn't explicitly cover error scenarios, so I'm treating the core requirement as just the create-and-write sequence.\n\nMocking lets me verify that the code invokes the right filesystem calls, but it doesn't confirm those operations actually succeed on a real system. To truly validate that a directory gets created and a file gets written, I need a real filesystem. That's why integration testing becomes necessary here.\n\nConsider what could go wrong: if the path construction has a bug (like improper handling of trailing slashes), mocking would miss it. Permission errors would also slip through. A unit test with mocked calls would catch if the code fails to invoke `os.makedirs` or passes the wrong path, but it wouldn't catch OS-level failures or content formatting issues that only surface with actual file I/O.\n\nThe behavior requires real filesystem operations—creating a directory and writing a file. Unit tests with mocks verify the code structure, not whether these operations actually succeed. Integration testing is the minimum level needed to confirm the loader genuinely creates the directory and writes the defaults file to the filesystem.\n\n**Minimum level: Integration**\n\n**Confidence: Unit 0.20, Integration 0.70, System 0.05, Workflow 0.05** assertions). But truly verifying the behavior works requires Integration level testing.\n\nThe distinction matters: catching a failure at the lowest possible level differs from realistically catching it. A realistic test avoids excessive mocking—for filesystem operations, that means using the actual filesystem. Permission errors and other real-world scenarios naturally surface at Integration level rather than requiring a separate System test.\n\n**Minimum level: Integration**\n\n**Confidence: Unit 0.15,