an be caught with real broken YAML in a unit test rather than mocking the library itself, giving high confidence at 0.95. Directory creation and defaults file generation represent a real failure mode that requires testing whether the code actually creates the necessary structure. level testing isn't applicable since there are no subprocess calls, external processes, or OS-level features involved. Agentic testing also doesn't apply—none of these behaviors depend on LLM non-determinism or unpredictable AI model outputs. Workflow-level testing isn't needed either, as there are no multi-step agent pipelines or sequential agentic operations.\n\nThis means my confidence should shift toward unit and integration testing. For the first behavior, unit tests can reliably verify the logic with high confidence (0.95), with only a small portion (0.05) requiring integration validation. For the second behavior, unit tests with mocks handle most cases well (0.85), but integration testing is still needed to catch filesystem-specific issues like permission errors (0.15).\n\nThe remaining behaviors follow similar patterns. Behavior 3 leans heavily toward unit testing (0.90) with minimal integration needs (0.10). Behavior 4 is almost entirely unit-testable (0.95), needing only slight integration coverage (0.05). Behavior 5 requires more integration testing since it involves actual filesystem operations—creating directories and writing files—so I'd weight it at 0.10 unit and 0.90 integration, accounting for real-world permission and path issues that only surface with actual filesystem interaction.\n\nNow examining plan_consistent for each: Behavior 1's test focuses on error message validation, which a unit test with mocked config loading handles completely—no integration needed. Behavior 2 tests path construction logic relative to a specific directory, including edge cases like trailing slashes. A unit test with mocked filesystem functions should verify this adequately. Behavior 3 checks